Technically, there <i>is</i> a native SGML mechanism called <i>link process declaration</i> (without DSSSL) for assigning style properties to document markup. Looks as follows:<p><pre><code>    &lt;!DOCTYPE html [
      &lt;!-- ... declarations
           for HTML elements, 
           attributes ... --&gt;
    ]&gt;
    &lt;!LINKTYPE render
      html #IMPLIED [
       &lt;!ATTLIST a color
         (blue|red) #IMPLIED&gt;
      &lt;!LINK #INITIAL
        a [ color=blue ]&gt;
    ]&gt;
    &lt;html&gt;
    &lt;title&gt;Blue link&lt;&#x2F;title&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;this &lt;a href=x.html&gt;
      link&lt;&#x2F;a&gt; is rendered
      in blue color&lt;&#x2F;p&gt;
    &lt;&#x2F;html&gt;
</code></pre>
Beyond this trivial example, style properties (link attributes) can be assigned in a context-dependent way for eg even&#x2F;odd pages in print, or actually capture the largest part of CSS selectors (sans pseudo-attributes such as :hover though which are &quot;magical&quot; in CSS).<p>I always wondered why people believed we need a distinct property universe for CSS properties when regular HTML attributes are there for this exact purpose (in link processes, attributes reuse regular content attribute declaration syntax).

Here is an iovec version, doing it all in a single writev.<p><pre><code>  #include &lt;unistd.h&gt;
  #include &lt;stdlib.h&gt;
  #include &lt;string.h&gt;
  #include &lt;alloca.h&gt;
  #include &lt;sys&#x2F;uio.h&gt;

  int main(int argc, char **argv)
  {
    if (argc &gt; 1) {
      int nstr = argc - 1;
      char **svec = argv + 1;
      int i, j;
      struct iovec *iov = alloca(sizeof *iov * nstr * 2);
      for (i = 0, j = 0; i &lt; nstr; i++, j += 2)
      {
        iov[j].iov_base = svec[i];
        iov[j].iov_len = strlen(svec[i]);
        iov[j + 1].iov_base = &quot; &quot;;
        iov[j + 1].iov_len = 1;
      }
      iov[j - 1].iov_base = &quot;\n&quot;;
      writev(STDOUT_FILENO, iov, j);
    }

    return 0;
  }
</code></pre>
#include &lt;numerous_caveats.h&gt;. We are not checking that everything got written, let alone handling a partial write. Systems have some limit on how many elements you can have in the iov array passed to writev.

Yes!  For example, in the GSS-API the various complex, opaque objects in the C bindings are specified in the RFC (2744) as:<p><pre><code>   typedef &lt;platform-specific&gt; gss_ctx_id_t;
   typedef &lt;platform-specific&gt; gss_cred_id_t;
   typedef &lt;platform-specific&gt; gss_name_t;
</code></pre>
Sadly this is always a pointer in actual implementations, but should have been a handle, where a handle is a structure containing two fields: an index or pointer-like value, and a <i>verifier</i> that can be used to check that the handle is [still] valid.  Using a handle would have made it possible to get much better memory safety.
